xpect was that Mazikeen would reciprocate, however slightly, Beatrice's feelings for her.  Yes, I realize that her kissing Beatrice was meant mainly as a &quot;fuck you&quot; to Heaven and the host.  But then on the last page we have Beatrice transferred to Lucifer's cosmos, in her birthday suit.  Could it be that Mazikeen has more than a utilitarian interest in Beatrice?  And if so, how would Lucifer feel about it?  Mind you, the devil doesn't go by human moral standards, so he may not care what Maz does in her spare time.<br>
<br>
Moving on to less coarse matters, I liked Lucifer's parting words to his brother.  (Mike, I'll bet that the English teacher in you couldn't resist using the word &quot;chiasm.&quot;  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  )  Clearly, their relationship is strained at best.  But I sense that Lucifer has a considerable amount of respect for Michael, if not vice versa.  Perhaps, in the end, they will come to some sort of understanding, if not a reconciliation. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#111111><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> failedangel</span><br> <span class=usertitle>Unregistered User</span><br>   <font color=#FFFF99>(11/20/03 9:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=29.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Lucifer #44 Discussion Thread</span><hr size=1> Back on the coarse side, though, that looks like it's Mazikeen's bed Beatrice wakes up in - Mazi's half-mask and sword are hanging on the wall just behind Beatrice.<br>
<br>
And on the not-so-coarse side, Beatrice's love for Maz seems rather like Maz' love for Lucifer - maybe Maz sees something of that in Beatrice?<br>
<br>
Anyway, however it works out between the three of them, let's hope Maz keeps her face the way it is - hard enough to have relationship-talks at the best of times, but if all you can do is slur a la Frankenstein's monster, how's it ever going to be managed? Especially now she's up against a Luci who seems to have got back his line in quips bigtime.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> sstewart</span><br> <span class=usertitle>Unregistered User</span><br>   <font color=#FFFF99>(11/21/03 7:24 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=29.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re:  Lucifer #44 discussion thread</span><hr size=1> Great job on 44, Mike!<br>
<br>
It's always hard to do a time-travel story well, and one of the tricks is, I believe, that you have to make the whole thing a closed loop, to at least try to ameliorate the paradoxes.  We had the setup in front of us the whole time, so it worked out really well.  As to why the Titans were able to walk outside of time -- Lucifer said it was their virtue, so I'm willing to go with that.  Hopefully no one else will have that virtue.<br>
<br>
Was the &quot;shit-spawn&quot; statement actually a pun on &quot;kopros&quot; vs. &quot;chaos&quot;?<br>
<br>
I also assumed that Lucifer's omnipresence comment referred to the Titans, not himself.  After all, it came right after Uriel's concern that the Titans were already at the SC.  I interpreted Lucifer's response more along the lines of &quot;No, they're not here just yet, unless they can be everywhere at once now, which I doubt.&quot;<br>
<br>
This is really a book that rewards the faithful reader.  Most of the complaints from reviewers seem to center around Beatrice and how they don't remember who she is.  But this is supposed to be an epic, after all! <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#111111><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/blucifer.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mcpeckham>mcpeckham</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 87<br> <font color=#FFFF99>(11/22/03 9:17 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=29.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re:  Lucifer #44 discussion thread</span><hr size=1> Interesting observations Sstewart!<br>
<br>
I think Mike gets around the time-walking issue by only certifying a handful of ancient gods -- in this case two of the children of Chaos by proxy of Mother Earth -- and avoids the physics questions because this is dark fantasy and not hard SF where it would obviously require structured explanations, or at least structured conjecture.<br>
<br>
I'm not sure about kopros (dung, manure) being a chaos pun, since technically the Greek word ÷Üïò is in fact (transliterated) simply chaos.<br>
<br>
The reason I read the omnipresence statement as perhaps relative to Lucifer and not the titans was that Lucifer says it in reaction to one of the host expressing alarm that such-and-such has arrived.  He says they're still some ways off, and then comments that omnipresence will be tough to master.  I read it as him attempting to use it to verify that they actually *were* still some distance off, since technically, how else would he know?<br>
<br>
On the other hand, the word omnipresence suggests manifestation, so you could very well be right.  If Mike had really intended it to be about Lucifer's awareness, he might've said simply omniscience and not omnipresence.<br>
<br>
Matt <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/blucifer.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sstewart@lucifer>sstewart</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#FFFF99>(11/22/03 2:38 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=29.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re:  Lucifer #44 discussion thread</span><hr size=1> My Greek is definitely rusty, so I could certainly be wrong about “kopros” being a pun – it just seemed appropriate, because the Titans were generated from chaos.  But you're right, it's kappa v. chi, so it could be a stretch.<br>
<br>
You’re also correct about this being a fantasy, not hard SF.  I prefer to speculate that the Titans were unique creatures and as the children of Chaos were actually not constrained by time in the same way as other beings.  In that sense they existed simultaneously in all times, and were vulnerable in some of them – but no one but themselves could reach back in time to hurt them.  So Lucifer actually subverted their own skill because he couldn’t go back in time himself.  But even this might be thinking too hard.  Lucifer just pulled out one of his nasty tricks, and that’s that.  If you assume that it was the Titans' uniqueness that lead to their destruction, though, then if anyone else manages to sit in the Primum Mobile it wouldn’t be possible to destroy them in the same way, if at all.<br>
<br>
I really think the omnipresence comment was regarding the Titans.  Based on everything that transpired it seems fairly clear that Effrul is about as far from the Silver City as it is possible to be, and Lucifer probably had a pretty good idea how long it would take for them to walk there. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#111111><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> failedangelI think Luci says somewh</span><br> <span class=usertitle>Unregistered User</span><br>   <font color=#FFFF99>(11/22/03 4:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=29.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Lucifer #44 discussion thread</span><hr size=1> I definitely took the omnipresence comment to be referring to the Titans - and there's been no indication that Lucifer's brief sit-down in the Primum Mobile gave him any &quot;new&quot; powers, let alone ones equal to YHVH's. (Given that the Titans had already usurped YHVH's &quot;place&quot; in a cosmic sense, it hardly could). Luci hasn't, so far, shown himself either omnipresent, omniscient /or/ omnipotent - he didn't see the Duinum coming, for instance, but needed Mazikeen's warning.<br>
<br>
And powerful as Luci is, it's always seemed clear he is less powerful than his father, even when his powers were not reduced by cards, angry Shinto deities, or deranged cherubs. He needed to go off to a vantage point to see Sandalphon's pocket world, and he couldn't move fast enough to make it back to the Luciverse in time to stop the Basanos sneaking in (unless we are to think that an entity capable of omnipresence would have to run places)<br>
<br>
Maybe that could be put down to YHVH hogging the place of power all to himself. I think Luci says somewhere that he and Michael were given powers equal to YHVH's but then prevented from using them. <br>
<br>
(Though come to think of it, YHVH's omniscience was never really demonstrated beyond his annoying tendency to go &quot;I knew you would do that&quot; after the fact - the hissy fit he threw at Michael for trying to save Elaine I suppose could be read as either bad faith or genuine surprised indignation. Similarly, his omnipotence was not really proved beyond the &quot;all part of my plan&quot; routine, and omnipresence hasn't really been indicated in the story until his leaving was described as involving extricating himself from his creation at the sub-atomic level) <br>
<br>
Given that Luci and Michael's powers seem to be complementary to each other though, it seems more likely that YHVH split between them powers that he himself possessed undivided. <br>
<br>
There's obviously bigger issues here about what omnipresence etc. would mean anyway, and religious exegesis, but in terms of how Mike's set out the relations between the characters within the story, this seems to me like the best explanation. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> failedangel</span><br> <span class=usertitle>Unregistered User</span><br>   <font color=#FFFF99>(11/23/03 4:30 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=29.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>    &gt; Re: Lucifer #44 discussion thread</span><hr size=1> um, so how does the edit function on posts work, exactly? Like just after you've had a cut-and-paste accident with your username? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#111111><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/blucifer.showUserPublicProfile?gid=wulfenbach>wulfenbach</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#FFFF99>(12/7/03 10:09 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=29.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Lucifer #44 discussion thread</span><hr size=1> I'm another vote for omnipresence referring to the Titans.  They were the ones mastering God's power, after all.  As for how Lucifer knows stuff, he's always had limited omniscience, if you know what I mean.  I think he had an early line about some details being on the surface and easy to read -- he knows things about mortals he sees, and can even see into the future a bit (or extrapolates very well, but he's made good predictions, unless you think those were cruel manipulations of the future.)  And Elaine had the power to see back in time, and we saw Meleos trying to crash-course her in long-distance scrying... and I think some of that might be extendible into limiited omnipresence.  He seemed to be saying her spirit form wasn't tied to that or any location... I end up with the image of a 'viewpoint', switchable at will, or something like the Endless, where if they let themselves go they can fill up the universe, and reappear nearly anywhere.<br>
<br>
Also note when Lucifer was racing back to his universe, the narrator lines about being able to girdle the world in an instant.  The implications of which I'm not sure we've always seen consistently, but anyway.<br>
<br>
'omni-' isn't quite the right word here; it's more the ability to know anything you want, or go anywhere you want -- vs. God's omniattention almost, knowing and being everything and everywhere at once.<br>
<br>
Lucifer had better respect Michael; I think Michael's the one being who can destroy him at will.<br>
